canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that a metallic material or alloy exhibits, contains, or is characterized by a specific metallurgical/microstructural phase or structure under the stated conditions.
Indicates that a structure, phase, feature, or process is present in or takes place within a given material or material class.

Indicates that the subject material exhibits a microstructure that is similar in type or characteristics to that of the object material, possibly in a specific context such as weld metal or heat-affected zones.
Indicates that two entities can be used in place of one another because they serve a similar functional role in a given application context.
Links a broader category or class to one of its more specific subtypes within a taxonomic or classification hierarchy.
Indicates that the subject is a more specific subtype, category, or member class within the broader object class in a taxonomy.
Indicates that the subject alloy or material contains the object element as an intentional alloying constituent, with some (possibly variable) concentration.
Indicates that the subject has intrinsic resistance to, or is less affected by, the damaging or corrosive action of the object (e.g., a corrosion mechanism).
Indicates that the subject, typically an alloying element or modifier, causally contributes to or increases the resistance of a material system to the specified damaging or corrosive mechanism.
Indicates that two entities are presented or classified together as peer items within the same document section, list, or taxonomy, without implying causal, hierarchical, or structural dependency.
A process or condition changes the microstructure of a material, typically affecting its phases, morphology, or distribution of microstructural features.
A process or entity generates or leads to the formation of a product, feature, or outcome.
Indicates that the subject inhibits, suppresses, or effectively prevents the occurrence of a specified degradation or metallurgical process in the given material context.
